==A==

{{glossary}}

{{term|absolute}}
{{defn|no=1|The absolute invariant is essentially the [[j-invariant]] of an elliptic curve.}}
{{defn|no=2|An absolute invariant is something fixed by a group action, in other words a (relative) invariant (something that transforms according to a character) where the character is trivial.}}

{{term|allotrious}}
{{defn|See {{harvs|txt|last=Sylvester|year=1853|loc=Glossary p. 543–548}}, Archaic.  }}

{{term|alternant}}
{{defn|no=1|An archaic term for the commutator ''AB''–''BA'' of two operators ''A'' and ''B''. {{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.144}} }}
{{defn|no=2|An [[alternant matrix]] is a matrix such that the entries of each column are given by some fixed function of a variable. }}

{{term|annihilator}}
{{defn|An annihilator is a differential operator representing an element of a Lie algebra, so that invariants of a group are killed by the annihilators. {{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.108}} }}

{{term|anti-invariant}}
{{defn|A relative invariant transforming according to a character of order 2 of a group such as the symmetric group.}}

{{term|anti-seminvariant}}
{{defn|{{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.126}} }}

{{term|apocopated}}
{{defn|See {{harvs|txt|last=Sylvester|year=1853|loc=Glossary p. 543–548}}. Archaic.}}

{{term|Arf invariant}}
{{defn|{{main|Arf invariant}} An invariant of quadratic forms over a field of order 2.}}

{{term|Aronhold invariant}}
{{defn|One of the two generators of degrees 4 and 6 of the ring of invariants of ternary cubic forms. {{harv|Dolgachev|2012|loc=3.1.1}} }}

{{term|asyzygetic}}
{{defn|Linearly independent.}}

{{glossary end}}

==B==

{{glossary}}

{{term|Bezoutiant}}
{{defn|1={{main|Bezoutiant}} A symmetric square matrix associated to two binary forms. }}

{{term|Bezoutic}}
{{defn|See {{harvs|txt|last=Sylvester|year=1853|loc=Glossary p. 543–548}}. Archaic.}}

{{term|Bezoutiod}}
{{defn|See {{harvs|txt|last=Sylvester|year=1853|loc=Glossary p. 543–548}}. Archaic.}}

{{term|bidegree}}
{{defn|An ordered pair of integers, giving the degrees of a form relative to  two sets of variables.}}

{{term|biform}}
{{defn|A polynomial homogeneous in each of two sets of variables. In other words an element of  S<sup>''m''</sup>''V''&times;S<sup>''n''</sup>''W'', usually considered as a representation of  GL<sub>''V''</sub>×GL<sub>''W''</sub>.}}

{{term|binary}}
{{defn|Depending on 2 variables. Same as bivariate.}}

{{term|biquadratic}}
{{defn|Same as quartic, meaning degree 4.}}

{{term|biternary}}
{{defn|A biternary form is one in 6 variables, 3 transforming according to the fundamental representation of SL<sub>3</sub> and 3 transforming according to its dual.}}

{{term|bivariate}}
{{defn|Depending on 2 variables. Same as binary.}}

{{term|Boolian invariant}}
{{defn|An invariant for the orthogonal group. {{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.344}} }}

{{term|bordered Hessian}}
{{defn|An alternative name for the reciprocant}}

{{term|bracket}}
{{defn|An invariant given by either the pairing of a vector and a vector in the dual space, or the determinant of a matrix form by ''n'' vectors of an ''n''-dimensional space (in other words their exterior product in the top exterior power).}}

{{term|Brioschi covariant}}
{{defn|This is a degree 12 order 9 covariant of [[ternary cubic form]]s, introduced by {{harvtxt|Brioschi|1863}}. {{harv|Dolgachev|2012|loc=3.4.3}} }}

