==C==

{{glossary}}

{{term|canonical form}}
{{defn|A particularly simple representation of a form, such as a sum of powers of linear forms, or with many zero coefficients. For example, the canonical form of a binary form of degree 2''m''+1 is a sum of ''m''+1 powers of linear forms.}}

{{term|canonisant}}
{{term|canonizant|multi=y}}
{{defn|{{main|canonizant}} A covariant of a form, given by the catalecticant of the penultimate emanant. It is related to the  canonical form of a form. For example, the canonizant of a binary form of degree 2''n''–1  has  degree ''n'' and order ''n''. {{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.21}} }}

{{term|catalecticant}}
{{defn|{{main|catalecticant}} An invariant vanishing on forms that are the sum of an unusually small number of powers of linear forms.}}

{{term|Cayley Ω process}}
{{defn|{{main|Cayley's Ω process}} A certain differential operator used for constructing invariants.}}

{{term|Cayleyan}}
{{defn|{{main|Cayleyan}} A contravariant. }}

{{term|characteristic}}
{{defn|See {{harvs|txt|last=Sylvester|year=1853|loc=Glossary p. 543–548}} }}

{{term|class}}
{{defn|The class of a contravariant or concomitant is its degree in the covariant variables. See also degree and order.}}

{{term|Clebsch invariant}}
{{defn|{{harv|Dolgachev|2012|loc=p.283}} }}

{{term|co-Bezoutiant}}
{{defn|See {{harvs|txt|last=Sylvester|year=1853|loc=Glossary p. 543–548}}. Archaic. }}

{{term|cogredient}}
{{defn|Transforming according to the natural representation of a linear group. {{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.55}} }}

{{term|combinant}}
{{defn|A joint relative invariant of several forms of the same degree, that is unchanged if a multiple of one of the forms is added to another. Essentially a relative invariant of a product of two general linear groups. {{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.340}} {{harvs|txt|last=Sylvester|year=1853|loc=Glossary p. 543–548}} {{harv|Salmon|1885|loc=p.161}} }}

{{term|combinative}}
{{defn|Related to invariants of a product of groups. For example a combinative covariant is a covariant of a product of two groups.}}

{{term|commutant}}
{{defn|A generalization of the determinant to arrays of dimension greater than 2. {{harv|Cayley|1860}} }}

{{term|complete}}
{{defn|A complete system of invariants is a set of generators for the ring of invariants.}}

{{term|concomitant}}
{{defn|A relative invariant of GL(''V'') acting on the polynomials over ''S''<sup>''n''</sup>(''V'')&oplus;''V''&oplus;V*.}}

{{term|conjunctive}}
{{defn|See {{harvs|txt|last=Sylvester|year=1853|loc=Glossary p. 543–548}} }}

{{term|connex}}
{{defn|A form in two sets of variables, one set corresponding to a vector space and the other to its dual, or in other words an element of the symmetric algebra of ''V''&oplus;''V''* for a vector space ''V''. Introduced by Clebsch.}}

{{term|continuant}}
{{defn|{{main|Continuant (mathematics)}} A determinant of a [[tridiagonal matrix]].{{harv|Salmon|1885|loc=p.18}} }}

{{term|contragredient}}
{{defn|Transforming according to the dual of the natural  representation of a linear group. {{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.74}} }}

{{term|contravariant}}
{{defn|A relative invariant of GL(''V'') acting on the polynomials over ''S''<sup>''n''</sup>(''V'')&oplus;''V''.}}

{{term|convolution}}
{{defn|A method of constructing invariants from two other invariants. {{harv|Glenn|1915|loc=p.87}} }}

{{term|covariancy}}
{{defn|{{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.83}} }}

{{term|covariant}}
{{defn|no=1|(Noun) A relative invariant of GL(''V'') acting on the polynomials over ''S''<sup>''n''</sup>(''V'')&oplus;''V''*.}}
{{defn|no=2|(Adjective) Invariant under the action of a group, especially for functions between two spaces acted on by the group.}}

{{term|cross ratio}}
{{defn|The [[cross ratio]] is an invariant of 4 points of a projective line.}}

{{term|cubic}}
{{defn|(Adjective) Degree 3}}
{{defn|(Noun) A form of degree 3}}

{{term|cubicovariant}}
{{defn|A covariant of degree 3, in particular an order 3 degree 3 covariant of a binary cubic given by the Jacobian of the cubic and its Hessian. {{harv|Elliott|1895|loc=p.50}} }}

{{term|cubinvariant}}
{{defn|An invariant of degree 3.}}

{{term|cubo-}}
{{defn|Used to form compound adjectives such as cubo-linear, cubo-quadric, and so on, indicating the bidegree of something. For example, cubo-linear means having degree 3 in the first of two sets of variables and degree 1 in the second.  }}

{{term|cumulant}}
{{defn|The numerator or denominator of a continued fraction, often expressed as a determinant. {{harvs|txt|last=Sylvester|year=1853|loc=Glossary p. 543–548}}.  }}

